{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514634"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:24:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:24:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12342"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12342"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.37,0.02,0.54,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4862"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77216"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4862"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62723"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"489"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7849"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39191"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44285"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77216"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of left leg pain and swelling. She has a medical history of hypertension, for which she takes perindopril. She has a 20 pack-year smoking history and drinks two glasses of wine at weekends. Her parent had a history of venous thrombosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her left leg is swollen and tender, with the left calf circumference 2 cm larger than the right. There is no erythema or warmth. An ultrasound reveals a non-compressible, hypoechoic area in the left popliteal vein.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Warfarin","Low molecular weight heparin","Aspirin","Apixaban","Unfractionated heparin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and ultrasound features consistent with deep vein thrombosis (DVT). The most appropriate initial treatment is \u003Cstrong\u003Eapixaban\u003C/strong\u003E, a direct oral anticoagulant (DOAC). DOACs are preferred first-line for DVT due to their rapid onset, fixed dosing, no requirement for routine monitoring, and favorable safety profile compared to traditional anticoagulants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as initial therapy as it requires 5-7 days to reach therapeutic effect and needs bridging with parenteral anticoagulation. It also requires regular INR monitoring and has numerous food and drug interactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow molecular weight heparin\u003C/strong\u003E was previously the standard initial treatment for DVT. While effective, it requires subcutaneous injection and is now mainly reserved for bridging anticoagulation and cases where DOACs are contraindicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for treatment of acute DVT. While it has a role in preventing arterial thrombosis, it is ineffective for treating venous thromboembolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnfractionated heparin\u003C/strong\u003E requires continuous intravenous administration and frequent monitoring of activated partial thromboplastin time (APTT). It is mainly used in patients with severe renal impairment or those who may need rapid reversal of anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating anticoagulation, patients should be assessed for underlying risk factors for DVT, including inherited thrombophilias given the family history. Compression stockings may be considered to prevent post-thrombotic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["DOACs are the initial treatment of choice for acute DVT in most patients due to their efficacy, safety profile, and ease of administration","Clinical features of DVT include unilateral leg swelling, pain, and tenderness","Non-compressibility on ultrasound is diagnostic of DVT"],"references":["Moheimani F, Jackson DE. Venous thromboembolism: classification, risk factors, diagnosis, and management. ISRN Hematol. 2011;2011:124610. doi: 10.5402/2011/124610. Epub 2011 Oct 17. PMID: 22084692; PMCID: PMC3196154.","Stone J, Hangge P, Albadawi H, Wallace A, Shamoun F, Knuttien MG, Naidu S, Oklu R. Deep vein thrombosis: pathogenesis, diagnosis, and medical management. Cardiovasc Diagn Ther. 2017 Dec;7(Suppl 3):S276-S284. doi: 10.21037/cdt.2017.09.01. PMID: 29399531; PMCID: PMC5778510."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62723"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12342"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19762"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19762"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d61e1b3c-7f5a-41bb-bd07-5e7e97b0e42c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d61e1b3c-7f5a-41bb-bd07-5e7e97b0e42c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":844,"height":1500}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62723","links":{"self":"https://app.e